lity to adjust the scale, character, and location of their global operations, international corporations have become increasingly sensitive to the kind and degree of tax obligations imposed on them by both host and home countries. Tax rules affect the volume of foreign direct investment, corporate borrowing, transfer pricing, dividend and royalty payments, and research and development. National governments that tax the profits of international firms face important challenges in designing tax policies to attract them. This collection examines the global ramifications of tax policies, offering up-to-date, theoretically innovative, and empirically sound perspectives on a problem of immense significance to future economic growth around the globe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBusiness. 0aInvestments, Foreign. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aAltshuler, Rosanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClausing, Kimberly A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Julie H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCummins, Jason G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrubert, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHand, John R. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHines, James R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHines, James R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJaffe, Adam B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewlon, T. Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShackelford, Douglas A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwenson, Deborah L., econtribu